{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17512776","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17512776"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:00:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:00:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11949"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11949","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11949"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.82,0.04,0.03,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4545"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75005"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4545","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4545"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11949"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60511"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"281"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6755"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6793"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25967"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42691"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75005","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75005"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 26-year-old woman is brought to the Emergency Department by her housemates due to concerns regarding her mental state. This morning she has been confused and acting erratically. She has been unwell for three days with diarrhoea. Her friends state that she has been seeing an endocrinologist for years but had recently ceased her prescribed medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears agitated and diaphoretic. Her pulse rate is 138/min, blood pressure 130/45 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, and temperature 38.4\u00b0C. An electrocardiogram shows an irregularly irregular rhythm with no discernible P waves and narrow QRS complexes.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Adrenal insufficiency","Thyroid storm","Neuroleptic malignant syndrome","Carcinoid syndrome","Parathyroid crisis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Ethyroid storm\u003C/strong\u003E, a life-threatening endocrine emergency characterised by severe thyrotoxicosis. The diagnosis is clinical, based on the presence of fever, tachycardia, central nervous system dysfunction (agitation, confusion), and gastrointestinal symptoms (diarrhoea). The recent cessation of antithyroid medications is a common precipitant. The irregularly irregular rhythm on ECG suggests atrial fibrillation, which commonly occurs in thyroid storm.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdrenal insufficiency\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with fatigue, postural hypotension, and electrolyte disturbances (hyperkalaemia, hyponatraemia). The agitated state and hypertension in this case would be unusual for adrenal insufficiency, which more commonly presents with lethargy and hypotension.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeuroleptic malignant syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E can present with hyperthermia, autonomic dysfunction, and altered mental status. However, it typically occurs in patients taking antipsychotic medications and is characterised by muscle rigidity and elevated creatine kinase, which are not described in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarcinoid syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E can cause flushing and diarrhoea but typically presents with episodic symptoms and would not explain the confusion or atrial fibrillation. It is usually associated with a known neuroendocrine tumour.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParathyroid crisis\u003C/strong\u003E, or hypercalcaemic crisis, presents with severe hypercalcaemia causing confusion, constipation, and renal dysfunction. The tachycardia and fever would be unusual, and there is typically a known history of hyperparathyroidism or malignancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EManagement of thyroid storm requires a multimodal approach including beta-blockers (e.g., propranolol) to control sympathetic overactivity, thionamides (e.g., propylthiouracil) to block new hormone synthesis, and supportive care. The mortality rate remains high (8-25%) even with appropriate treatment.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Thyroid storm is an acute and life-threatening complication of hyperthyroidism with an estimated mortality of 8-25%","Thyroid storm is a clinical diagnosis characterised by fever, tachycardia, and central nervous system dysfunction","Recent cessation of antithyroid medications is a common precipitant of thyroid storm"],"references":["Pokhrel B, Aiman W, Bhusal K. Thyroid Storm. [Updated 2022 Jun 19]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK448095/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60511"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11949"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60511","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60511"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-28T20:14:50+10:30"